		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Barbarian Warrior</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:stehlek@uswest.net">Kudadan</a> | 
		            4/8/1999 3:05:11 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">So, you like the idea of having a warrior that can stomp, and still have a bit of mental capacity? Perhaps the Barbarian Warrior is for you!<BR>
Starting Out:<BR>
You begin inside of Halas, at the northern tip of Antonica, largest of the three continents. First things first - arrange your hot buttons as you like, and head for the Warrior's Guild. The Pit is where you'll find your guildmaster. I trained up a trade skill, tailoring, because I just really had to have one of those Polar Bear headdresses for my helmet. The other skills will improve as you use them, 1H slashing, kick, sense heading, etc. Note: I put most of my points into Intelligence, which really helps your skills improve faster.<BR>
Now, off to Everfrost! You can get out of Halas on the ferry (slow and wimpy) or by swimming to the exit area (builds your swimming fast). I prefer to swim.<BR>
Once outside, you'll find Everfrost to be made of many narrow paths and wide intersections. For the first few levels, stick to killing the decaying skeletons, gnoll pups, and goblin whelps. Be careful though, the last two have a nasty habit of ganging up on you! Stick near the guards, and RUN if you need to. You're a barbarian, though, so you can take a little more punishment than other warriors. Make sure you use your kick whenever the button is raised! It may not seem like much, but every bit helps.<BR>
Be careful in Everfrost when running around. Make a note of trees and rocks to get your bearings. Sense heading should be used at all times to build it up, as well as know which way you're headed. I put a total of 15 points into Tailoring after gaining two more levels. Then I went out hunting for Polar Bear cubs, to get their pelts. After getting some money together, as well as a few pelts, I began to make my armor. It will take a few tries to get it right, and may cost a few gold, but soon you'll be head to toe in polar bear skin. My warrior is at a 26 tailoring, and I still fail about 1 in 6 times when making patchwork. <BR>
After you make level 5 or 6, you will find it easier to group with others and partake in my current favorite activity: Mammoth hunting. I'm not talking about the big woolies, I mean the calfs. A group of four warriors and two shamen of levels 5, 6, and/or 7 should be able to take one down. Other good targets are the snow orc troopers, regular polar bears, and snow leopards. These fights are long, even with a full group, so your weapon skills should build up nicely. In between hunting, you may try a quest or two, or just do what I call &quot;cash runs.&quot; I beat up skeletons for the money, weapons, and the bone chips they provide. There may be quicker ways of making cash quickly, but I haven't found it yet. Your choice of weapons is up to you: one-handers are good with a shield (better AC) but two-handers do a lot more damage. I find the weapon and shield works well for me, but if you max the skill out, and are a ways away from the next level, you may try switching weapon types to make yourself more versatile.<BR>
When you get to learn the dodge skill, put just one point into it. It will improve on it's own at a moderate pace. You may try building up another trade or weapon skill for more options, as by this time your training for the &quot;core&quot; skills you've been using all along will cost a lot of money to improve, and money is something we need to save. <BR>
Why are we saving all this money? Depends on what you want to do, myself, I want to become a smith as well, and the tools and basic items cost a lot of money. (Note: I haven't found anybody in Halas that sells ore, you may need to head for Qeynos or Rivervale for that). Another reason to save money is for better arms and armor. These are VERY expensive.<BR>
Other good ways to earn money would be fishing (always good, but a little tedious at times), questing (groups are good for this), and selling patchwork. I usually sell for around 2g to other players. You can sell to the stores for about 1g 5s, but it's better to be nice to your fellow barbarians, and offer to them first. <BR>
Other places for adventure - Black Burrow is good. But, if someone shouts &quot;Train!!&quot; - run for the Zone exit. Nothing worse than 6 big knoll warriors coming down on top of you. There is also a lot of profit and experience to be made in Black Burrow, and a group is the best way to do this. <BR>
Well, your mileage may vary, but the above is a good introduction to starting a mighty barbarian from the north as you begin your new &quot;life&quot; in Norrath!!
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
